communes</link> within the province of Brindisi.</p>
<p>

Brindisi Rosso is made mainly from <assortment wordnetid="108398773" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../824/1666824.xml">
Negroamaro</link></assortment>
 grapes (at least 70%) and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../373/73373.xml">
Malvasia nera di Brindisi</link>; it can also contain smaller quantities of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../581/8497581.xml">
Sussumaniello</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../166/6132166.xml">
Montepulciano</link> and <assortment wordnetid="108398773" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../179/628179.xml">
Sangiovese</link></assortment>
.</p>

</sec>
<sec>
<st>
 Characteristics </st>
<p>

Brindisi Rosato wine is coral-pink in colour, tending towards pale cherry-red; the smell is delicately fruity; the flavour is dry, harmonious, with a mild and agreeable bitterness.</p>
<p>

